'''Hyperinflation therapy''' ('''HIT''') is a very common<ref name="pmid9849237">{{cite journal| author=Robson WP| title=To bag or not to bag? Manual hyperinflation in intensive care. | journal=Intensive Crit Care Nurs | year= 1998 | volume= 14 | issue= 5 | pages= 239–43 | pmid=9849237 | doi= | pmc= | url= }}</ref> therapy performed on patients who are suffering from some sort of respiratory distress.  The therapy involves applying volumes greater than normal to reinflate the collapsed alveoli in the lungs.  There are many different techniques used to administer hyperinflation therapy.<ref name="pmid16541603">{{cite journal| author=Ntoumenopoulos G| title=Indications for manual lung hyperinflation (MHI) in the mechanically ventilated patient with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. | journal=Chron Respir Dis | year= 2005 | volume= 2 | issue= 4 | pages= 199–207 | pmid=16541603 | doi= | pmc= | url= }}</ref>  The [[clinician|respiratory therapist]] typically decides which method is best for each patient.<ref name="pmid10573249">{{cite journal| author=Denehy L| title=The use of manual hyperinflation in airway clearance. | journal=Eur Respir J | year= 1999 | volume= 14 | issue= 4 | pages= 958–65 | pmid=10573249 | doi= | pmc= | url= }}</ref>

